This is the build log for RunHub. An honest account of what got built, why it got built that way, and what the process looked like from the inside.

It started with a spreadsheet and a frustration. It ended up as a full-stack iOS app deployed to a physical phone.

How it started
The Excel era
"Masta Tracka" the spreadsheet that did everything for me. HR zones, VO2 max trends, a calendar that understood travel. It worked because I built it for me.

Before RunHub, there was a spreadsheet. I called it Masta Tracka. It had five weeks of training summaries, heart rate zones, a visual calendar with color-coded travel and race days, VO2 max and lactate threshold pace charted over time, and a personal records table.

Strava wasn't cutting it. Garmin wasn't cutting it. None of the apps were wrong, they just weren't built around how I actually train and think about training. They logged what happened. They didn't help me plan or see where I was going.

So I kept building the spreadsheet. Added HR zones. Added a milestones table with goal times for upcoming races. Tracked resting heart rate alongside HRV to watch for overtraining. The spreadsheet became a real tool, ugly, slow, mostly manual, but mine.

RunHub started as the question: what if that spreadsheet were an app? Not a general running app with a feature checklist. A specific app, for a specific person, with the exact features that matter to that person's training.

Masta Tracka — the spreadsheet that RunHub grew out of. February 2026.
HR Zones + Weekly Summary Zones 1–5 calibrated personally. Five weeks of actual mileage, RHR, LT pace, and VO2 max tracked side by side.
Color-coded travel calendar Gray for flight days, purple for away days, yellow for race day. Became RunHub's trip event system almost verbatim.
VO2 Max / LT Pace chart Watching LT pace improve while VO2 Max held steady told a different story than just looking at mileage.
Goal + Milestones table For plotting my unreasonable goals and the milestones that would help me reach them.

The transition from spreadsheet to app wasn't just about going mobile. It was about keeping the intentionality. Every screen in RunHub traces back to something that existed in that spreadsheet, because both reflect the same actual training philosophy.

BUILD LOG
5 features  /  documented decisions
01
Dashboard

Getting the numbers on one screen

The first thing the app needed to do was show what the spreadsheet's summary table showed: weekly miles, year-to-date, average pace, runs per week. But it also needed to pull that data automatically. Strava OAuth handles the connection, every run syncs without any manual entry.

The stat cards at the top of the dashboard are reorderable. That decision came directly from how the spreadsheet was organized, different weeks I care about different things. The week before a race I want to see my most recent data. Mid-training block I want weekly mileage and frequency. Making it reorderable meant it could be that without needing separate modes.

Decision note

The week strip (Mon through Sun with mileage under each day) came from wanting to see the shape of a week at a glance. Not totals. Shape. Was Tuesday heavier than Thursday? Did the long run actually land on Saturday? A strip is faster to read than a list for that question.

02
Schedule

A calendar that understands travel

The spreadsheet's calendar was the feature I was most proud of and most annoyed by. I'd manually type "Flight to SD (Travel)" in a cell, Excel would change the background, then do the same for away days, then the race cell in yellow. Every trip was four or five manual edits to get the visual right.

RunHub flips that. Add a trip — enter the destination and travel dates and it generates the flight day event, the away day events, and it will link to whatever race falls that weekend if that's what the travel is for. The color coding from the spreadsheet maps directly to the app: Different colors, but Same system, zero manual work.

Decision note

The weekly mileage bar in the monthly view (the green line at the end of each row) was added because looking at a month of dots, one per run, doesn't tell you anything about load. The bar shows whether a week was high or low volume without you having to add it up. Weekly green progress bars show at a glance how mileage built or tapered across the month.

03
Race Planning

The races widget and why it syncs with the schedule

The milestones table in the spreadsheet had three columns: race name, goal time, date. That simplicity was the whole point. RunHub's race card on the dashboard is the same idea: name, goal, countdown in weeks. No fluff.

The one thing that needed solving: you should only have to enter a race once. Adding it in the Schedule tab creates the calendar entry and the dashboard race card at the same time. Both share an ID under the hood so edits stay in sync. The dashboard reflects the schedule; the schedule reflects the dashboard. There's no separate "Race" form hidden in settings somewhere.

Decision note

Goal time and actual time are tracked as separate fields. A lot of apps don't properly reflect these triumphs or defeats. Seeing both, what I was aiming for and what I ran, is the whole point of racing. The spreadsheet had both. The app has both.

04
Gear

Building a shoe catalog to simultaneously satisfy my consumerism

This one wasn't in the spreadsheet. It was a different frustration. I kept having browser tabs open comparing shoes. RunRepeat for scores and specs, manufacturer sites for pricing, Reddit threads for actual opinions. No single place had all of it with the ability to track what I actually owned or wanted.

The gear tab is 60+ shoes and growing, each with a RunScore 0–100, specs (drop, stack height, weight, carbon plate), a real product photo pulled through a custom backend image proxy and cached in Postgres so photos load instantly and don't break. Filter by category (daily, tempo, race, trail, recovery), sort by rating or price, search by name or brand. Add a shoe to Owned and track mileage. The app will flag when you're approaching replacement territory.

Decision note

The image proxy was the most technically interesting piece here. Third-party image URLs rot. The source CDN restructures and suddenly every shoe card is broken. Fetching images, storing the raw bytes in a Postgres BYTEA column, and serving them from our own endpoint means the catalog stays intact regardless of what happens upstream. 7-day cache headers mean repeat loads are instant.

05
Snapshot

Exporting training data as structured context

This one came from a specific workflow problem. When I wanted coaching feedback on a training block, from a coach, usually from ChatGPT, I was manually copying and pasting numbers. Week totals, pace trends, race goals, what my shoes were. It was tedious and I always left something out.

The snapshot export builds a structured Markdown document: configurable date range, selectable sections (activities, scheduled workouts, upcoming races, personal bests, gear rotation), and a weekly mileage breakdown. It shows an estimated token count so you know the size of what you're sending. Copy it and paste it wherever the conversation is happening.

Decision note

Markdown was the right format because it's human-readable, renders cleanly in basically every tool, and is structured enough for a reader to parse quickly.

What it runs on
TECHNICAL STACK
Layer Technology Role in the project
Mobile App Flutter / Dart Cross-platform iOS app. Riverpod handles all state as AsyncNotifier providers: each data domain (activities, races, gear, schedule events) is independently async with compile-time safety.
Backend API Node.js / Express REST API running on Railway. Handles Strava OAuth token exchange and refresh, all data persistence, and the image proxy endpoint for the gear catalog.
Database PostgreSQL Stores user auth tokens, calendar events, races, travel trips, personal bests. Also stores shoe imagery as BYTEA. The image proxy writes fetched bytes directly into Postgres so photos survive upstream CDN changes.
Deployment Railway Backend and database both hosted on Railway. Push to main deploys automatically. The physical iPhone connects to the live production backend.
Auth Strava OAuth 2.0 Full OAuth flow with deep link callback. Access tokens stored in flutter_secure_storage on device. Refresh handled server-side so tokens never expire mid-session.
State Riverpod AsyncNotifier providers for each domain. Gear, schedule events, races, and activities are all independently watchable. Provider composition keeps the dashboard reactive to changes in any of them.
Still open
What stays on the list
RunHub is deployed and running on my physical device. These are the features that are scoped but not yet shipped.
01
Improved data persistence
Races, personal bests, gear, and schedule events currently live in local state and a lightweight backend. The next layer is proper user accounts and syncing everything to Postgres so the app survives reinstalls and device switches.
02
Garmin, Polar, and COROS
The Connect tab has placeholders for all three. Garmin Developer Program approval takes one to two weeks. The pattern is established from Strava, same OAuth flow, same sync logic, different endpoints.
03
VO2 max and LT pace tracking
This was one of the most analytically rich part of the spreadsheet. Charting both over time, separately, made trends visible that a single fitness score hides. That dual-chart view is the next thing going into the dashboard.
04
Schedule Syncing
While this app adds another arrow to the quiver, I want to ease the burden by syncing with Apple or Google calendars.
